<!-- FAQ -->
<section class="cat-page-faq">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="cat-page-faq-head">
      <span class="eyebrow">Frequently asked questions</span>
      <h2>What patients ask us most about body treatments.</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="cat-page-faq-list">
      <div class="cat-page-faq-item open">
        <button class="cat-page-faq-q" type="button">How many post-operative drainage sessions do I need? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="cat-page-faq-a"><p>It depends on the surgery and the recovery stage, but the standard protocol is 8-12 sessions spread across the first 4-6 weeks post-op. During the diagnosis we review your medical report, surgery date and design the exact plan.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="cat-page-faq-item">
        <button class="cat-page-faq-q" type="button">Does wood therapy work against cellulite? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="cat-page-faq-a"><p>Yes, especially when combined with consistency (nutrition, hydration, movement). Wood therapy visibly improves the appearance of cellulite by stimulating circulation and drainage. It isn't magic, it's sustained manual work — and the results show.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="cat-page-faq-item">
        <button class="cat-page-faq-q" type="button">Do pressotherapy and wood therapy complement each other? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="cat-page-faq-a"><p>Very much so. Wood therapy works the fascia and subcutaneous fat manually; pressotherapy drains lymphatic fluid with sequential pressure. Combined within the same session, results multiply — it's one of the protocols we recommend most for heavy legs and cellulite.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="cat-page-faq-item">
        <button class="cat-page-faq-q" type="button">After a liposuction, when can I start the drainage? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="cat-page-faq-a"><p>Usually between 5 and 10 days after surgery, following your surgeon's instructions. The key point: specific post-operative drainage (not a generic massage) as soon as the doctor authorises it. The sooner you start, the better the recovery.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="cat-page-faq-item">
        <button class="cat-page-faq-q" type="button">Will the manipulation hurt? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="cat-page-faq-a"><p>Lymphatic drainage is very gentle — it doesn't hurt. Wood therapy and muscle recovery have a medium-high intensity depending on your tolerance, but always within the therapeutic threshold. If at any moment it becomes too much, we adjust. We never treat anyone enduring pain.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

